{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GZKHxDj15MeGqPwiEGvVUc","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LOGIC dataset fallacy classification argotario propaganda ElecDef\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"A multi-label graph-based dataset for fallacy classification ...\",\"url\":\"https://hal.science/hal-04834405v1/document\"},{\"title\":\"Argument-based Detection and Classification of Fallacies ...\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2023.emnlp-main.684.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Multitask Instruction-based Prompting for Fallacy Recognition\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2022.emnlp-main.560.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"\\\\dataset: A Dataset of News Comments with Common Logical Fallacies Written by LLM-Assisted Crowds\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.03457\"},{\"title\":\"FALCON: A Multi-label Graph-based Dataset for Fallacy\",\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/pdf/10.1145/3672608.3707913\"},{\"title\":\"Robust and Explainable Identification of Logical Fallacies in Natural\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2212.07425\"},{\"title\":\"Robust and explainable identification of logical fallacies in natural language arguments - ScienceDirect\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0950705123001685\"},{\"title\":\"Papers with Code - Logical Fallacies\",\"url\":\"https://paperswithcode.com/task/logical-fallacies\"},{\"title\":\"COCOLOFA: A Dataset of News Comments with Common ...\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.39.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Boosting Logical Fallacy Reasoning in LLMs via Logical Structure Tree\",\"url\":\"https://people.engr.tamu.edu/huangrh/papers/emnlp24-main.fallacy-reasoning.pdf\"}]\n\nHere is a summary of the search results related to **LOGIC dataset**, **fallacy classification**, **Argotario**, **propaganda**, and **ElecDef (ElecDeb60To16/20)**:\n\n## Key Datasets for Fallacy Classification\n\n### LOGIC and LOGICCLIMATE\nLOGIC and LOGICCLIMATE (13 fallacy types) include logical fallacies collected from online educational materials and climate change news articles, respectively. For the fine-grained classification evaluation, researchers use the LOGIC and LOGIC Climate datasets, which contain thirteen classes. The LOGIC dataset contains everyday fallacious arguments belonging to various topics.\n\n### Argotario\nThe Argotario dataset consists of five fallacies in dialogue between players in game settings. The five fallacy types are: Ad Hominem, Appeal to Emotion, Red Herring, Hasty Generalization, Irrelevant Authority, in addition to the No Fallacy type. Habernal et al. (2017) aimed to improve fallacy detection by creating a publicly available software called \"Argotario\".\n\n### ElecDeb60To20\nElecDeb60To20 (six fallacy types) comprises political debates from United States presidential candidates.\n\n### Propaganda Detection\nDa San Martino et al. (2019) annotated 451 news articles with 18 propaganda techniques, 12 of which qualify as logical fallacies. This task applies various logical fallacy techniques including Ad Hominem, Red Herring, Appeal to Emotion, and Irrelevant Authority, using the Propaganda Techniques Corpus (PTC).\n\n## Methods and Results\n\nAlhindi et al. experimented with different prompts and zero, few, and full-shot scenarios using the T5 model on the PTC-SemEval20, LOGIC, Argotario, COVID-19, and Climate datasets, achieving F1 scores of 56%, 66%, 64%, 28%, and 20%, respectively.\n\nKnowledge injection methods have been used to classify fallacies, achieving macro F1 scores of 82.7% and 57.3% on the LOGIC and LOGICCLIMATE datasets (13 classes), respectively.\n\nAlhindi et al. improved on this same setting by leveraging GPT-3.5 to generate examples to increase the representation of rare classes and incorporate additional contextual information.\n\n## Newer Contributions\n\nA comprehensive three-stage evaluation framework of detection, coarse-grained, and fine-grained classification was proposed, adapting existing evaluation datasets for each stage and employing three families of robust and explainable methods based on prototype reasoning, instance-based reasoning, and knowledge injection.\n\nMore recent work proposes a logical structure tree to explicitly represent and track the hierarchical logic flow among relations for detecting and classifying fallacies.\n\nThe FALCON dataset is a multi-label, graph-based dataset containing COVID-19-related tweets with expert annotations for six fallacy types—loaded language, appeal to fear, appeal to ridicule, hasty generalization, ad hominem, and false dilemma.\n\nThese results highlight that fallacy classification remains a challenging NLP task, with F1 scores varying significantly across datasets and methods, and that the intersection with propaganda detection is an active area of research.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"607fdfc9-907f-4bc3-829a-6743699977ac","uuid":"31f78113-2156-42a8-9f57-80ad2a6af910","tool_use_result":{"query":"LOGIC dataset fallacy classification argotario propaganda ElecDef","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_015eYRNcvpPgwF5p7pFZG4d1","content":[{"title":"A multi-label graph-based dataset for fallacy classification ...","url":"https://hal.science/hal-04834405v1/document"},{"title":"Argument-based Detection and Classification of Fallacies ...","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2023.emnlp-main.684.pdf"},{"title":"Multitask Instruction-based Prompting for Fallacy Recognition","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2022.emnlp-main.560.pdf"},{"title":"\\dataset: A Dataset of News Comments with Common Logical Fallacies Written by LLM-Assisted Crowds","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.03457"},{"title":"FALCON: A Multi-label Graph-based Dataset for Fallacy","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/pdf/10.1145/3672608.3707913"},{"title":"Robust and Explainable Identification of Logical Fallacies in Natural","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2212.07425"},{"title":"Robust and explainable identification of logical fallacies in natural language arguments - ScienceDirect","url":"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0950705123001685"},{"title":"Papers with Code - Logical Fallacies","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/task/logical-fallacies"},{"title":"COCOLOFA: A Dataset of News Comments with Common ...","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.39.pdf"},{"title":"Boosting Logical Fallacy Reasoning in LLMs via Logical Structure Tree","url":"https://people.engr.tamu.edu/huangrh/papers/emnlp24-main.fallacy-reasoning.pdf"}]},"Here is a summary of the search results related to **LOGIC dataset**, **fallacy classification**, **Argotario**, **propaganda**, and **ElecDef (ElecDeb60To16/20)**:\n\n## Key Datasets for Fallacy Classification\n\n### LOGIC and LOGICCLIMATE\nLOGIC and LOGICCLIMATE (13 fallacy types) include logical fallacies collected from online educational materials and climate change news articles, respectively. For the fine-grained classification evaluation, researchers use the LOGIC and LOGIC Climate datasets, which contain thirteen classes. The LOGIC dataset contains everyday fallacious arguments belonging to various topics.\n\n### Argotario\nThe Argotario dataset consists of five fallacies in dialogue between players in game settings. The five fallacy types are: Ad Hominem, Appeal to Emotion, Red Herring, Hasty Generalization, Irrelevant Authority, in addition to the No Fallacy type. Habernal et al. (2017) aimed to improve fallacy detection by creating a publicly available software called \"Argotario\".\n\n### ElecDeb60To20\nElecDeb60To20 (six fallacy types) comprises political debates from United States presidential candidates.\n\n### Propaganda Detection\nDa San Martino et al. (2019) annotated 451 news articles with 18 propaganda techniques, 12 of which qualify as logical fallacies. This task applies various logical fallacy techniques including Ad Hominem, Red Herring, Appeal to Emotion, and Irrelevant Authority, using the Propaganda Techniques Corpus (PTC).\n\n## Methods and Results\n\nAlhindi et al. experimented with different prompts and zero, few, and full-shot scenarios using the T5 model on the PTC-SemEval20, LOGIC, Argotario, COVID-19, and Climate datasets, achieving F1 scores of 56%, 66%, 64%, 28%, and 20%, respectively.\n\nKnowledge injection methods have been used to classify fallacies, achieving macro F1 scores of 82.7% and 57.3% on the LOGIC and LOGICCLIMATE datasets (13 classes), respectively.\n\nAlhindi et al. improved on this same setting by leveraging GPT-3.5 to generate examples to increase the representation of rare classes and incorporate additional contextual information.\n\n## Newer Contributions\n\nA comprehensive three-stage evaluation framework of detection, coarse-grained, and fine-grained classification was proposed, adapting existing evaluation datasets for each stage and employing three families of robust and explainable methods based on prototype reasoning, instance-based reasoning, and knowledge injection.\n\nMore recent work proposes a logical structure tree to explicitly represent and track the hierarchical logic flow among relations for detecting and classifying fallacies.\n\nThe FALCON dataset is a multi-label, graph-based dataset containing COVID-19-related tweets with expert annotations for six fallacy types—loaded language, appeal to fear, appeal to ridicule, hasty generalization, ad hominem, and false dilemma.\n\nThese results highlight that fallacy classification remains a challenging NLP task, with F1 scores varying significantly across datasets and methods, and that the intersection with propaganda detection is an active area of research."],"durationSeconds":26.86965879799996}}
